translated: Ahlberg, Albert Natanael, chief physician, Apelviksstrand, b. May 23, 1899 in Wollsjö, Malmöhus. 1st son of director Otto A. and Hilda Svensson. Married to Frida Engström in 1929. Children: Gerd b. 1932, Anita b. 1937. - Graduated from Lund University with a degree in medicine in 1923, licensed medical practitioner in 1929, and received a medical doctorate there in 1940. Studied in Germany in 1930, France, Finland, Estonia in 1935, Finland, Belgium, Denmark, and Norway in 1946. Assistant physician and acting attending physician at Norrtälje Hospital in 1929, attending physician at the orthopedic department at Malmö General Hospital from 1929 to 1932, attending physician at the radiology department there from 1932 to 1933, attending physician at the surgical department there from 1933 to 1935, 2nd attending physician at Västerås Hospital surgical department from 1935 to 1937, 1st attending physician at the disability home in Gothenburg from 1937 to 1939, attending physician at the coastal sanatorium in Apelviken from 1939 to 1940, acting chief physician there from 1940 to 1941, and chief physician since 1941. Member of the Swedish Orthopedic Association board of directors in 1945. Wrote "Studien über 111 nachuntensuchte Fälle von Calcaneus-Frakturen" (degree of dependency 40) and several other writings on orthopedics, limb surgery, and social issues. Received the Royal Finnish Order of the Lion, Order of the Cross of Liberty (Finland), Medal of Honor (Belgium), and Danish Freedom Medal with the inscription "for meritorious tuberculosis work."
